==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*legra-'', from Indo-European ''*legh-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''leger'', Old Saxon [[legar]] (Dutch [[leger#Dutch|leger]] ‘bed, camp, army’), Old High German [[legar]] (German [[Lager]] ‘camp’), Old Norse [[legr]] (Swedish [[läger]] ‘bed’), Gothic [[𐌻𐌹𐌲𐍂𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[λεκτρον]], Latin [[lectus]] ‘bed’, Celtic ''*leg-'' (Old Irish [[lige]], Irish [[luighe]]), Slavic ''*ležati'' (Russian [[лежать]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'lejeɹ/

===Noun===
'''leġer''' ''n''
# the state or action of [[lying]], lying down, or lying ill
#:''On ðam sixtan dæge his legeres'': on the sixth day of his illness.
# a resting-place; a [[couch]], a [[bed]], a death-bed, a [[grave]]
#:''On gehalgodan legere licgan'': to be buried in a consecrated grave.

